h3. Issue Summary

Status is invisible in edit mode when using [Status Macro|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/status-macro-223222355.html] 
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Install Confluence 7.1.1
 # Create a page that includes Status Macro.
 # Upgrading Confluence from 7.1.1 to 7.6.2 and restore the content
 # On viewing the restored page in 7.6.2 in edit mode, the status is invisible.

I noticed the issue is not seen on the newly added Status Macro to the restored page. 
h3. Expected Results

Status colors to be displayed correctly in edit mode.
h3. !image-2020-08-24-16-56-03-815.png|width=425,height=184!  

!Status.png|width=733,height=464!

 
h3. Actual Results

Status colors are not displayed/formated correctly in edit mode. 
h3. !image-2020-08-24-16-56-19-678.png|width=414,height=283!  

!Status2.png|width=685,height=395!

 
h3. Workaround

Temporary Workaround
 # Navigate to *General Configuration* > *Stylesheet*
 # Add the following snippet there - the color codes are taken from [Lozenges - AUI Documentation|https://docs.atlassian.com/aui/8.5.1/docs/lozenges.html]
{code:css}
.status-macro.aui-lozenge {
    background-color: #DFE1E6;
    border-color: #DFE1E6;
    color: #42526E;
}

.status-macro.aui-lozenge.aui-lozenge-error {
    background-color: #BF2600;
    border-color: #BF2600;
    color: #FFFFFF;

}

.status-macro.aui-lozenge.aui-lozenge-success {    
    background-color: #00875A;
    border-color: #00875A;
    color: #FFFFFF;
}

.status-macro.aui-lozenge.aui-lozenge-removed {    
    background-color: #BF2600;
    border-color: #BF2600;
    color: #FFFFFF;
}

.status-macro.aui-lozenge.aui-lozenge-current {    
    background-color: #0052CC;
    border-color: #0052CC;
    color: #FFFFFF;
}

.status-macro.aui-lozenge.aui-lozenge-moved {    
background-color: #FFF0B3;
    border-color: #FFF0B3;
    color: #172B4D;
}
{code}
 # Save the config

h3. Issue Summary
When a Jira Issue Date event is created on Team Calendars using 2 custom fields for Date Time Picker, if the event is *exactly* 24h, the event does not display the 24h range, instead, it displays only on the start date. If using TC 6.0.47 it shows only on the end date.
 !image-2020-08-20-13-55-18-469.png|thumbnail! 
h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Setup an applink between Confluence and Jira;
# Create two custom Date Time Picker fields on Jira;
# Set up the first field to 6/30/2020 6:30 PM and the second one to 7/1/2020 6:30 PM;
# On Team Calendars, create an event with the Jira Issue Dates type;
# Select these fields for the start and end date.

h3. Expected Results
The event range appears from 6/30/2020 6:30 PM to 7/1/2020 6:30 PM.

h3. Actual Results
The event range appears only on one of the days. The event start and end date/time changes to show only a day and the checkbox "All day event" is checked.

h3. Workaround
Change one of the fields so the date will be 24h01min.
For example, instead of 
{panel}starting date/time = *6/30/2020 6:30PM* and final date/time = *7/1/2020 6:30PM*{panel} 
use
{panel}starting date/time = *6/30/2020 6:30PM* and final date/time = *7/1/2020 6:31PM*
{panel}

h3. Issue Summary
Updates from Jira instance, e.g. comments, mentions and shares don't show Workbox notifications in Confluence.

h3. Environment
Both Confluence & JIRA instance have been integrated to one another via Application Link and [Workbox Notifications have been configured to include Jira notifications as well|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/configuring-workbox-notifications-301663830.html#ConfiguringWorkboxNotifications-IncludingnotificationsfromJira].

h3. Steps to Reproduce
On the Jira instance:
# Leave a comment with an @ mention to a user in a Jira issue
# Open the Workbox with that user in Confluence

h3. Expected Results
New updates are being displayed in the configured Confluence Workbox notifications.

h3. Actual Results
New updates aren't being displayed in the configured Confluence Workbox notifications, with no apparent errors thrown in either atlassian-jira.log or atlassian-confluence.log files.

(i) With the debug logging enabled ({{com.atlassian.mywork}}) in both Confluence and Jira, we could see the below exception is thrown in the atlassian-jira.log file:
{noformat}
2020-07-12 20:02:07,671-0600 http-nio-8081-exec-22 url:/jira/rest/api/...DEMO-333/comment username:test DEBUG test 10.20.32.60,0:0:0:0:0:0:0:1 /rest/api/2/issue/DEMO-333/comment [c.a.m.client.service.HostServiceImpl] HostIdCache contained [REGISTERED_HOST] none()
{noformat}

h3. Cause:
By default, the _mywork-confluence-host-plugin_ do have preventive mechanism which will force refresh this cache value should the existing value is {{NULL}} as shown in the code snippet below.
{code:java|title=HostServiceImpl.java}
    private Option<ApplicationLink> lookupAppLink(final HostType hostType) {
        final Option<ApplicationId> hostId = hostIdCache.getHost(hostType.name());
        if (hostId != null) {
            log.debug("HostIdCache contained [{}] {}", hostType, hostId);
            return hostId.flatMap(toAppLink);
        } else {
            log.debug("HostIdCache didn't contain any info on [{}]; forcing a refresh of host info", hostType);
            return updateHostAvailability().get(hostType);
        }
    }
{code}
However, as what we've observed from the log snippet above - the {{HostIdCache}} is currently being recognised as *not {{NULL}}* since its current value is set to *{{none()}}*. Because of this, the force refresh mechanism then won't be triggered by _mywork-confluence-host-plugin_ automatically. This is a bug in the _mywork-confluence-host-plugin_.

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behaviour. A workaround will be added here when available

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-13477].
  {panel}

{quote}
Thai text don't have space between words. Usually, a dictionary-based algorithm is used to break string into words. For Lucene to be usable for Thai, we need to use an Analyzer that know how to break Thai words is needed.

Lucene now included ThaiAnalyzer (org.apache.lucene.analysis.th.ThaiAnalyzer).

After I read Confluence document, I know that I can switch Lucene Analyzer to others Analyzer such as German, Russian to support indexing on these language on Administration > Site Configuration > Formatting and International Settings Section > Indexing Language field.

But I didn't see Thai as a choice
{quote}

h3. Problem Definition

Currently, Synchrony does not support ARM platforms. The Collaborative Editing feature fails for Confluence running on ARM platforms.

Synchrony fails with the below error:
{code:java}
2020-08-18 06:25:26,728 DEBUG [461:StdOutHandler [/home/ubuntu/tmp/jdk-11.0.8+10-jre/bin/java]] 2020-08-18 06:25:26,727 WARN [async-dispatch-9] [synchrony.sync.hubs] [FAILED_TO_LOAD_NATIVE_LIBRARY] no native library is found for os.name=Linux and os.arch=aarch64 {:entity "/Synchrony-fbdf18d7-2caa-31dd-a3da-a74dc81c54ee/confluence-65603", :throwable #error {
2020-08-18 06:25:26,728 DEBUG [461:StdOutHandler [/home/ubuntu/tmp/jdk-11.0.8+10-jre/bin/java]] 	 :cause "[FAILED_TO_LOAD_NATIVE_LIBRARY] no native library is found for os.name=Linux and os.arch=aarch64"
2020-08-18 06:25:26,728 DEBUG [461:StdOutHandler [/home/ubuntu/tmp/jdk-11.0.8+10-jre/bin/java]] 	   :message "[FAILED_TO_LOAD_NATIVE_LIBRARY] no native library is found for os.name=Linux and os.arch=aarch64"
{code}
h3. Suggested Solution

Add support to ARM platforms to Confluence server.

h3. Issue Summary
Changing the title of certain pages fails and it reverts to the old name. When we edit the page again, we see the old page's title.

Further tests reveal that this happens when there are pages with "content_status='draft' and creationdate=null".
h3. Steps to Reproduce

We can confirm this issue affects you by running the following SQL query:
{code:sql}
select * from content where content_status = 'draft' and creationdate is null;
{code}
h3. Expected Results
Able to edit the page's title
h3. Actual Results
Changing the title of certain pages fails and it reverts to the old name. When we edit the page again, we see the old page's title.

h3. Workaround

We can add a random entry in the creationdate field for pages with content_status=draft:
{code:sql}
update content set creationdate='2020-01-25 11:05:32' where content_status = 'draft' and creationdate is null;
{code}

At this moment, most popular macro does not cache the results. As a result, a page with a "most popular macro" would be slow (30 seconds or even more).

We need a solution which allows to cache data. Cache TTL must depend on the space/site size.

There should be an option to disable this cache via a new system variable:
{code:java}
-Dconfluence.popular-label-macro.disable-cache=true {code}

h3. Issue Summary
The Clean Temporary Directory job successfully deletes the files but the logs show a warning. This does not happen when you run the job manually.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Configure a Confluence instance;
# Start Confluence;
# Head to _General Configuration > Scheduled Jobs_;
# Next to Back Up Confluence, select _Run_ (this will generate a .zip file in the <confluence-home>/temp directory);
# Go to <confluence-home>/temp and note that the zip file for the back up is there;
# Wait until the time set for the job to run (4:20 am by default);
(i) Note: Because Confluence backup is set to remain on the folder for 24h, you may have to wait until the next day or the zip won't be deleted. Unless you're affected by this bug.

h3. Expected Results
# The zip file is successfully removed from the directory;
# There is no error on the logs.

h3. Actual Results
# The zip file is successfully removed from the directory;
# The logs show this warning:
{code:java}
2020-07-29 04:22:05,659 WARN [Caesium-1-1] [impl.schedule.caesium.JobRunnerWrapper] runJob Scheduled job webhooks.history.daily.cleanup.runner#webhooks.history.daily.cleanup.job completed unsuccessfully with response JobRunnerResponse[runOutcome=FAILED,message='IllegalStateException: No Hibernate Session bound to thread, and configuration does not allow creation of non-transactional one here']{code}

h3. Workaround
Since the job is working, the only workaround, for now, is to ignore the warnings on the logs.
